'''Michael James Whale''' (born 13 May 1951), known professionally as '''James Whale''', is an English radio personality, television presenter, podcast host and author. He gained initial prominence in the 1980s as the host of ''The James Whale Radio Show'' on [[Radio Aire]] in Leeds, which was simulcast on national television. From 1995 to 2008, Whale hosted a night time radio show on [[talkSPORT]], followed by stints on [[LBC 97.3]] and various BBC radio stations.

Whale is the current host of his podcast ''The James Whale Show'' and a night time radio show on [[Talkradio|talkRADIO]].

==Early life==
Michael James Whale was born on 13 May 1951 in [[Ewell]], Surrey into "an ordinary middle class family".{{sfn|Whale|2007|p=17}} His English father David worked in the family business S&R Whale, which made dresses, aprons and overalls in a factory in [[Brixton]], London.{{sfn|Whale|2007|p=17}} His Welsh mother Anne (''[[née]]'' Price) was a professional ballet dancer.{{sfn|Whale|2007|p=18}} His parents later owned The Famous Green Man pub in Ewell.<ref name=timeleisure>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeandleisure.co.uk/articles/local/4238-james-whale.html|title=Having a Whale of a time|work=Time & Leisure|first=Chris|last=Wood|accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> Whale has a younger brother, Keith.{{sfn|Whale|2007|p=17}} Whale did not enjoy his school life. After failing his [[eleven-plus]] exam, he attended Linton's Lane Secondary Modern School and Longmead County Secondary Boys School, both in Epsom.{{sfn|Conversations|2017|loc=00:00:48–00:01:33}}<ref>''Almost a Celebrity: A Lifetime of Night-Time'' Author: James Whale. Retrieved: 10 November 2011.</ref>

From fourteen to sixteen, Whale took up archery and became a Surrey junior champion.<ref name=timeleisure/> He relocated to the [[Kings Cross, London|King's Cross]] area of London where his parents ran a pub.<ref name=timeleisure/> He wanted to become an actor, but his mother advised him to "get a proper job".{{sfn|Conversations|2017|loc=00:02:43–00:04:01}} Among Whale's first jobs was as a trainee buyer for [[Harrods]].<ref name=independent2008>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/my-life-in-media-james-whale-830556.html|title=My Life in Media: James Whale|date=19 May 2008|first=Jamie|last=Merrill|work=The Independent|accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> In this job he came into contact with a DJ which influenced him to become one soon after, citing [[Tony Blackburn]], [[Johnnie Walker (DJ)|Johnnie Walker]] and [[Kid Jensen]] as among his favourites.{{sfn|Conversations|2017|loc=00:04:01–00:06:47}} After learning that Watneys was to open a chain of discos, Whale took their DJ training course and landed his first gig at The Bird's Nest in [[Muswell Hill]], north London. He found the experience "dull", but realised he had an ability to introduce records and worked at a Watney's venue in Sweden for several months.{{sfn|Conversations|2017|loc=00:07:24–00:09:31}} Upon returning home Whale resumed DJ work, took acting lessons and worked as a rep, but earned little money.{{sfn|Conversations|2017|loc=00:09:31–00:10:12}}

==Career==
===1970–1995: Early career and ITV television show===
Whale began his broadcasting career in 1970 following a visit to a [[Topshop]] store on [[Regent Street]], London. He spoke to manager [[Ralph Halpern]] who initially declined to hire a DJ for the store, after which he worked as an assistant stage manager at a theatre in Oxford. Whale was soon invited back to Topshop and accepted work as one of the launch DJs of Radio Topshop, the in-house radio station.{{sfn|Conversations|2017|loc=00:10:12–00:11:20}}<ref name=independent2008/> In 1974, he became the host of an evening talk radio show at [[Metro Radio]],<ref name=independent2008/> serving northeast England from studios in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]]. He was the first presenter of the ''Nightowls'' program. During this time, Whale took up additional work as a voice over artist and acting roles in ''[[Doctor Who]]'' and ''[[Z-Cars]]''.<ref name=independent2008/> In 1980, he moved to [[Radio Derby]]<ref name=independent2008/> to host a morning phone-in, working with [[Terry Christian]] who later became a colleague at talkSPORT.

In 1982, Whale joined [[Radio Aire]] in [[Leeds]] to host the night talk show; by 1987 he moved to the morning slot before returning to evenings. In 1987, he released two singles: "The Whaley Rap"/"I Hear James (On the Radio)"<ref>{{cite AV media notes|url=https://www.discogs.com/James-Whale-Co-The-Cigar-Store-Indians-Whaley-Rap/release/2269486|title=Whaley Rap!|others=James Whale and Co.|year=1987|id=AIRE 1}}</ref> and "Wrap it Up for Xmas". By late 1987, the radio show was simulcast on [[Red Rose Radio]] from [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]]. In 1989, Whale's third single, "Bimbo", entered the UK top 100 singles chart. An edited version of the B-side, "A Big Big Egg", was the closing theme for his TV show.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}

In the late 1980s, Whale became influenced by American radio hosts, including "[[shock jock]]" [[Howard Stern]], and changed his style, having become tired of the "lovely phone-ins" that he had been accustomed to.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/260271051/|title=The rift of the gab|newspaper=The Guardian|date=18 September 1989|page=23|first=Nigel|last=Fountain|accessdate=28 June 2018|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> Commencing on the night of Friday 18 November 1988, Whale's radio show at Radio Aire was simulcast with [[Yorkshire Television]] and was titled ''The James Whale Radio Show'',<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/260345468/|title=Television and Radio – Yorkshire|newspaper=The Guardian|date=23 September 1988|page=40|accessdate=28 June 2018|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> featuring live studio guests, music and listener phone calls. The show became a ratings success, and after several months it started to air nationally on [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]].<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/258428232/|title=The James Whale Radio Show|newspaper=The Observer|date=2 October 1988|page=77|accessdate=28 June 2018|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> Conservative MP [[Jerry Hayes]] had a regular slot on the show and [[Steve Coogan]] would also make a regular appearance. By September 1989, the show attracted over one million viewers. It cost the television station £15,000 to run each hour.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/259068049/|title=Whale of a time on the cheap|newspaper=The Observer|date=3 September 1989|page=63|first=Nicholas|last=Fraser|accessdate=28 June 2018|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|subscription=yes}}</ref>

In January 1993, Whale began a new ITV series, ''Whale On''<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/260294002/|title=Television – ITV London|newspaper=The Guardian|date=8 January 1993|page=28|accessdate=28 June 2018|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> and in 1994 he presented a weekend afternoon show on [[LBC]] in London. He also presented ''The Blue Whale'' on [[Men and Motors]].

===1995–2008: Talk Radio/talkSPORT===
From 1995 to 2008, Whale hosted a talk show on weekday nights on [[talkSPORT]] from 10pm to 1am. ''The James Whale Show'' featured as guests celebrities such as [[Jodie Marsh]], [[David Icke]], [[Nick Pope (journalist)|Nick Pope]], [[Alex Jones (radio)|Alex Jones]], [[David Shayler]], [[Lembit Öpik]], [[Myleene Klass]], [[Peter Stringfellow]] and [[Alistair McGowan]]. Another regular guest was the psychic [[Uri Geller]]. Whale's friend [[Bernard Manning]] would often telephone on his way from gigs. On two occasions, Whale and American talk host [[Tom Leykis]] co-hosted shows that ran simultaneously as episodes of both their programmes.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}

Whale participated in a live ''[[Newsnight]]'' programme on 26 April 2007 on [[BBC Two]], broadcast simultaneously on [[talkSPORT]], in which he referred to two-week refuse pickup throughout the UK and the 'scandal' of [[global warming]]. Whale should have had a live link to the Newsnight studio, but due to a technical failure this was not possible. Whale announced he believed [[climate change denial|global warming was solely a natural phenomenon]]. He described [[recycling]] as a 'joke' and believed prisoners should sort rubbish and recyclable waste.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}

In May 2008, Whale was sacked because he twice called on listeners to vote for [[Boris Johnson]] before the [[London mayoral election, 2008|London mayoral election in 2008]].<ref name="bbc">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7385370.stm |title=Radio host James Whale is sacked |work=BBC News |accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> [[Ofcom]] fined Talksport £20,000, saying he had "seriously breached the due impartiality rules at the time of an election".

===2008–2013: LBC===
On 7 May 2008 Whale said he would join [[Bid TV]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7387773.stm|title= Sacked DJ Whale becomes TV host|publisher=BBC News|date=7 May 2008|accessdate=7 May 2008}}</ref> He continued to broadcast on JamesWhaleRadio.co.uk. On 20 May 2008, Whale began a four-hour weekly evening phone-in on [[Internet radio station]] [[Play Radio UK]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/may/12/radio2?gusrc=rss&feed=media | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Whale to host web radio talkshow | first=John | last=Plunkett | date=12 May 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref> however, on 2 September 2008 he said on air he was leaving Play Radio for book promotion and TV work. He said he would continue his blog.

After standing in for [[Clive Bull]] on [[LBC 97.3]] for six days in August 2008, Whale covered for [[Nick Abbot]] for two weeks from 29 September 2008 on LBC. In November the same year, he began presenting the drivetime show on LBC between 4{{nbsp}}pm and 7{{nbsp}}pm every weekday.<ref>{{cite web|author=(22:00-00:00) |url=http://www.lbc.co.uk/whale-takes-over-lbc-drivetime-show-4417 |title=Whale takes over LBC Drivetime show |publisher=LBC |date=9 November 2011 |accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref><ref>Plunkett, John. [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/sep/09/commercialradio.radio "James Whale back on the radio as drivetime host of LBC 97.3"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 9 September 2008. Retrieved on 6 May 2009.</ref> In March 2013, it was announced that existing presenter Iain Dale would replace him in this time slot as Whale's contract was not renewed.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}

===2013–2016: Various projects===
After leaving [[LBC 97.3]] Whale presented shows at [[BBC Radio Berkshire]], [[BBC Three Counties Radio]], [[BBC WM]], occasionally [[BBC Radio Kent]] and a new online format of his hit 1989 TV show, ''Whales Weekly''.

In September 2013, Whale launched his weekly podcast, ''The James Whale Radio Show'',<ref name=playerfm>{{cite web|url=https://player.fm/series/james-whale-radio-show|title=The James Whale Radio Show|publisher=Player.fm|accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> which was produced by Rob Oldfield. The podcast has since run for over 240 original episodes.<ref name=playerfm/> He also hosted the first season of the show ''The Book Show'', along with producer and co-host [[Paul Andrews (producer)|Paul Andrews]], which was broadcast on the Sky satellite channel ''Information.TV'' from 2013 to 2014.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}

On 13 December 2013, Whale announced that he would be the new permanent presenter of the [[BBC Essex]] breakfast programme. He presented his last show on the station on 23 September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/THEJamesWhale/status/411466202234781696 |title=Tweet |publisher=Twitter |date=13 December 2013 |accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref> He also hosted "Something for the Weekend" on [[BBC Radio Kent]] Saturday mornings from 10{{nbsp}}am until 2{{nbsp}}pm.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}

On 28 July 2016, Whale entered the ''[[Celebrity Big Brother (UK TV series)|Celebrity Big Brother]]'' house to compete as a housemate in its [[Celebrity Big Brother 18|eighteenth series]]. He was the sixth to be evicted, coming ninth overall.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://bigbrother.channel5.com/housemate/james-whale|title=Housemate profile|date=4 August 2018|work=Channel5|access-date=4 August 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>

===2016–present: talkRADIO===
Whale began covering shows on [[Talkradio|talkRADIO]] in October 2016 and he started presenting the Monday to Thursday evening show between 7{{nbsp}}pm and 10{{nbsp}}pm from 7 November 2016. This show reunited Whale with former producer Ash.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Roy|title=James Whale to host evenings on talkRADIO|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2016/11/james-whale-to-host-evenings-on-talkradio/|publisher=Radio Today|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref> 

In August 2018, Whale was suspended by talkRADIO, pending a full investigation, after an interview with a woman who had been sexually assaulted. talkRADIO subsequently described the interview as having been "conducted in a manner that did not reflect the values of the station and completely lacked sensitivity".<ref>{{cite News|last=Radio|first=Talk|url=http://talkradio.co.uk/news/statement-talkradio-following-james-whale-show-monday-30-july-18080327466|title=TalkRadio's James Whale suspended over insensitive interview|work=TalkRadio|date=4 August 2018|accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref> In a video clip from the interview, Whale was seen laughing when the interviewee described what had happened to her.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/aug/03/talkradios-james-whale-suspended-over-victim-interview|title=TalkRadio's James Whale suspended over rape victim interview|last=McKay|first=Jessica|date=3 August 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=5 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45064393|title=James Whale suspended over rape interview|date=4 August 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=5 August 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> Whale returned to the air on 13 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/talkradios-james-whale-back-on-air-after-suspension-over-interview-with-alleged-sex-assault-victim-that-lacked-sensitivity/|title=Talkradio's James Whale back on air after suspension over interview with alleged sex assault victim that 'lacked sensitivity'|work=Press Gazette|first=Charlotte|last=Tobitt|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>

==Personal life==
In 1970, Whale married Melinda Maxted. They have two sons, James and Peter.<ref name="jameswhalefund">{{cite web|url=http://www.jameswhalefund.org/AboutUs_trustees.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061126165711/http://www.jameswhalefund.org/AboutUs_trustees.html |archive-date=26 November 2006 |dead-url=yes |title=Bio at the James Whale Fund site |accessdate=13 April 2015 |df= }}</ref> In February 2018, Whale announced that Maxted had been diagnosed with stage four lung cancer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/it-was-a-huge-shock-james-whale-reveals-wife-melinda-has-terminal-lung-cancer-a3765706.html|title=Radio host James Whale reveals wife Melinda has weeks to live|publisher=|accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> She died on 12 May 2018.

In February 2000, Whale was diagnosed with [[kidney cancer]]. He had not experienced any symptoms until he noticed blood in his urine, caused by a large tumour on his left kidney. He underwent an operation from which he had a 50% chance of survival, and chose not to have chemotherapy afterward.<ref name=guardian2014>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/mar/19/james-whale-cancer-hasnt-changed-me|title=James Whale: 'Cancer hasn't changed me, I'm still miserable and difficult'|date=19 March 2014|work=The Guardian|first=Sarah|last=Johnson|accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> In 2006, he launched the [[James Whale Fund for Kidney Cancer]] to fund research and raise awareness of the disease.<ref name=independent2008/> The fund became Kidney Cancer UK in 2016.

Whale has often spoken of his [[dyslexia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdadyslexia.org.uk/downloads/goodpractice.pdf|title=DFS 110<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=Bdadyslexia.org.uk|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> and is a patron of the National Literacy Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nla.org.uk/patrons.php|title=National Literacy Association - Our Patrons<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=Nla.org.uk|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>

